    <h2>Flowers in Indian Culture: A Colorful Tapestry</h2>
    <p>In India, flowers aren't just pretty faces - they're woven into the very fabric of life! From temple offerings to
        festive decorations, these blooms play starring roles in daily rituals and grand celebrations. The lotus, for
        instance, isn't just a flower; it's a spiritual superstar in both Hinduism and Buddhism. And let's not forget
        the cheery marigolds, always ready to party at festivals and religious events. Roses and jasmines? They're the
        perfume industry's BFFs, filling the air with their intoxicating scents.</p>
    <h2>India's Floral Calendar: Blooms for Every Season</h2>
    <p>Mother Nature sure knows how to keep things interesting in India! Check out these seasonal showstoppers:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><span class="flower-name">Spring:</span> Rhododendrons paint the hills red, orchids show off their exotic
            beauty, and tulips add a dash of Dutch charm.</li>
        <li><span class="flower-name">Summer:</span> Bougainvilleas turn up the heat with their vibrant hues, plumerias
            (frangipani) perfume the air, and sunflowers follow the sun's lead.</li>
        <li><span class="flower-name">Monsoon:</span> Crossandras brave the rains, delicate rain lilies pop up
            overnight, and cosmos flowers sway in the wet breeze.</li>
        <li><span class="flower-name">Winter:</span> Dahlias dazzle with their variety, petunias carpet gardens in
            color, and chrysanthemums (guldaudi) light up the chilly days.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Poetic Petals: Flowers in Hindi Literature</h2>
    <p>Hindi poets have a long-standing love affair with flowers! They use these natural beauties to paint vivid word
        pictures:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The rose (gulab) - the eternal romantic, always ready for a love story</li>
        <li>The lotus (kamal) - floating serenely, inspiring spiritual growth</li>
        <li>Marigolds (genda) - bringing the party vibes to every occasion</li>
        <li>Jasmine (chameli) - the epitome of grace and sweetness in verse</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Flower Power: Ayurvedic Healing Blooms</h2>
    <p>In Ayurveda, India's ancient wellness wisdom, flowers aren't just for show - they're nature's medicine cabinet!
        Check out these floral healers:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Marigold (genda): Nature's anti-inflammatory superhero</li>
        <li>Jasmine (chameli): Your go-to for calm vibes and sweet dreams</li>
        <li>Hibiscus (gudhal): Bad hair day? Tummy troubles? Hibiscus to the rescue!</li>
        <li>Lotus (kamal): Good for your skin, great for your heart</li>
        <li>Chamomile (babuna): The ultimate chill pill for your body and mind</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Floral Fantasies in Indian Art</h2>
    <p>Indian artists have been crushing on flowers for centuries! From intricate temple carvings to delicate miniature
        paintings, flowers pop up everywhere. The lotus is like the ultimate celebrity, making cameos in countless
        artworks. And don't even get us started on textiles - saris, shawls, and tapestries bloom with floral patterns
        that'll make your eyes pop!</p>
    <p>Hungry for more flower facts? Buzz over to <a href="https://flowernames.org" target="_blank">Flower Names</a> and
        let your floral knowledge blossom!</p>
